- Bypass the Sampler group when trying to finalize masks.
- Un-mute HiRes Fix group for final render to increase image quality.

# Controlnet:
- Adjust weight values on Lineart, Depth, and Openpose to affect the output, will require experimentation.
- If you already have rendered Lineart, Depth, and Openpose videos, you can mute the Orange Generate groups and un-mute the Red Override groups and upload the respective videos to save on processing time.

# Input:
1. Input a subject video and select the max number of frames to load with frame\_load\_cap (if needed).
2. Select the output width and height of the video
3. You can set every\_nth to 2 or more to use every other frame to reduce rendering time if needed.
4. Start later in the video using skip\_frames.
4. Choose a seed value

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Subject Masks
- You can leave these on without issues for the most part
- Will convert red, green, and blue subjects in input mask video into separate masks.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Audio Processing:
- This section takes in audio from the input video, extracts the stems (bass, drums, vocals, etc.) and then converts it to a normalized amplitude synced with the input video frames.
- amp_control = total range the amplitude can travel.
- amp_offset = the minimum value the amplitude can take.
- Example: amp\_control = 0.8 and amp\_offset = 0.2 means the signal will travel between 0.2 and 1.0.

### Tips:
- Sometimes the Drums stem will have the actual Bass notes of the song, preview each to see which to use for your masks.
- Use the graphs to get a good understanding of how the signal for that stem changes over the length of the video

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Models:
- I recommend using an LCM model (I used ParadigmLCM v1.0) and adding the lora AnimateLCM\_sd15\_t2v\_lora.safetensors with strength 0.18.
- Set Loras in the Lora Stacker with associated weights.
- You can merge multiple models together using the Model Merge Stack to get various interesting effects. Make sure the weights add up to 1.0 for the enabled models.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# AnimateDiff:
- You can change or bypass the motion lora, I use LiquidAF with weight 0.8 by default.
- Increase/decrease the Scale and Effect floats to increase/decrease the amount of motion in the output.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# IPAdapters:
### Red, Green, Blue:
- Subject mask reference images.
### Black:
- Background mask image, upload a reference image for the background.
### White, Yellow, Magenta, Cyan:
- Dilation mask reference images, upload a reference image for each color dilation mask in use.


### Tip:
- Only un-bypass the IPAdapters you need to save on VRAM.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
# Audioreactive Dilate Masks:
- Adjust the min and max radius of the dilation mask which will grow and shrink depending on the current normalized amplitude value for that frame.
- Un-bypass different mask groups if you want to add additional audioreactive masks.
- You can change which subject the mask targets using the top-most node, by default it is set to subject\_mask\_red.
- You can also change which audio stem to base the audioreactivity on by changing the Get\_audio\_sync node from bass to drums and so on.
### Tips:
- Masks are composited from Back to Front, so set the largest radius on the White mask, and smaller on the Yellow, Magenta, with smallest on Cyan. If you can't see all the enabled colors this is probably why!
- 
- White is "behind" yellow which is "behind" magenta etc.
- Change the shape to "square" for faster processing speed when testing, it's less accurate but useful when setting things up.
- Un-mute Override Composite and mute the mask color groups if you have a composite video already rendered to save on processing time.
